AB  - This paper adopts the Leibenstein hypothesis that there are increasing returns to nutrition (over a range) for an individual's ability to work. This assumption generates unemployment in the models analyzed and allows a study of the effects of trade policy on employment and income distribution. The effects of world price changes, tariffs, production subsidies cum employment taxes, and production taxes cum employment subsidies are analyzed.
