AB  - The paper analyses the gap in earnings between white and colored people in South Africa in 1970 and 1980. The gap is decomposed into its ‘explained’ and ‘discrimination’ components and, from a model of occupational attainment, into wage-and job-discrimination. Job discrimination decreased between 1970 and 1980. Colored people in younger experience cohorts experienced a significant decline in discrimination between 1970 and 1980, most of which was due to a decline in job descrimination. Discrimination against those in older experience cohorts appears not to have declined.
